One very important point about the South variant , is that the primary selection pressure will not be to make it more infectious by being a better fit with the Ace 2 receptor , but the evasion of acquired immunity , either through natural infection , or by vaccination . We would expect to see such where there is a high incidence of previous exposure , and this , indeed , to be what in South . The good news is that its unlikely to suddenly stop all acquired immunity to disappear , but it will gradually degrade it . We are going to be a game of virus variant Whack - a - Mole for , and that is possibly an answer to those that question why the ordered , or for enough vaccine to give everybody in the 6 as , presumably the later can be to encompass more . I should add that I ' m particularly by the vaccine as it to me it ' s much faster to change and get new into the delivery chain at the same time as being robust . The are , at the moment at least , a bit too fragile for easy deployment and it ' s especially a problem in . However , they can be very fast with new being into production in ( approval depending ). Whilst the vaccine can also be in days , there remains a concern about acquired immunity to the viral vector . The Institute specifically chose a , rather than human for the vector as it was unlikely their would be any significant resistance to it in the human population . However , it might be that , if are subject to repeated of the vector , then immunity to that will make it a lot less effective over time . I suppose a new vector may be used , but that could well mean spending much more time on clinical for safety . In contrast , the and protein would seem much less likely to be vulnerable .
